	<div id="content">
		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">L4 microkernel family</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>L4</b> is a family of second-generation <a href="/wiki/Microkernel" title="Microkernel">microkernels</a> based on the original designs and implementations by <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">German</a> <a href="/wiki/Computer_scientist" title="Computer scientist">computer scientist</a> <a href="/wiki/Jochen_Liedtke" title="Jochen Liedtke">Jochen Liedtke</a>. Originally implemented as highly tuned <a href="/wiki/Intel_80386" title="Intel 80386">Intel i386</a>-specific <a href="/wiki/Assembly_language" title="Assembly language">assembly language</a> code,<sup id="cite_ref-Liedtke_93_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Liedtke_93-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/Application_programming_interface" title="Application programming interface">API</a> has seen extensive development in a number of directions, both in achieving a higher grade of <a href="/wiki/Platform_independence" title="Platform independence" class="mw-redirect">platform independence</a> and also in improving <a href="/wiki/Computer_security" title="Computer security">security</a>, isolation, and <a href="/wiki/Robustness" title="Robustness">robustness</a>. There have been various re-implementations of the original binary L4 kernel interface (<a href="/wiki/Application_binary_interface" title="Application binary interface">ABI</a>) and its higher level successors, including <b>L4Ka::Pistachio</b> (<a href="/wiki/Universit%C3%A4t_Karlsruhe_(TH)" title="Universität Karlsruhe (TH)" class="mw-redirect">Uni Karlsruhe</a>), <b>L4/MIPS</b> (<a href="/wiki/UNSW" title="UNSW" class="mw-redirect">UNSW</a>) and <b>Fiasco</b> (<a href="/wiki/TU_Dresden" title="TU Dresden" class="mw-redirect">TU Dresden</a>). For this reason, the name <b>L4</b> has been generalized and no longer only refers to Liedtke's original implementation. It now applies to the whole <a href="/wiki/Microkernel" title="Microkernel">microkernel</a> family including the L4 <a href="/wiki/Kernel_(computer_science)" title="Kernel (computer science)" class="mw-redirect">kernel</a> <a href="/wiki/Interface_(computer_science)" title="Interface (computer science)">interface</a> and its different versions.</p>
